post_text: I have been given permission from family to share. I am sad to share that Vi Nixon has passed away. Vi taught 3rd grade at Crescent from the early 1980’s to about 2003. She was very respected and loved by students and staff alike. Vi loved literacy and helping students to be better readers. I remember a great sense of humor and she was sooo proud of her students’ and children. I was a very young in-experienced teacher when I first started working and Vi was always supportive of me and all her Crescent Co-workers. I find it ironic that Vi has passed at a time when schools are closed and children are working from home. I bet a lot of parents out there would love a little advice from somebody like Vi. In closing I can hear the collegial joking that often took place between Vi and Jim Maynard. Oh the laughing!!! Nixon family thank you for sharing a gifted teacher with us. This picture was taken in 1983.
text: I have been given permission from family to share. I am sad to share that Vi Nixon has passed away. Vi taught 3rd grade at Crescent from the early 1980’s to about 2003. She was very respected and loved by students and staff alike. Vi loved literacy and helping students to be better readers. I remember a great sense of humor and she was sooo proud of her students’ and children. I was a very young in-experienced teacher when I first started working and Vi was always supportive of me and all her Crescent Co-workers. I find it ironic that Vi has passed at a time when schools are closed and children are working from home. I bet a lot of parents out there would love a little advice from somebody like Vi. In closing I can hear the collegial joking that often took place between Vi and Jim Maynard. Oh the laughing!!! Nixon family thank you for sharing a gifted teacher with us. This picture was taken in 1983.

post_text:
To begin: Everybody is safe.

Parents: During our afternoon bus run our west route bus encountered downed trees and power lines with two students one para educator and the bus driver on board.

The bus driver stopped on 112 and they remained on the bus as trained to do. 911 was called and Washington State Patrol, Clallam County Fire District 4, a Clallam County Deputy and Clallam County PUD responded. Additionally office staff contacted parents and transportation employees stood by to help if needed. The bus returned safely to school about 4:30 and the student was reunited with his parent.

David Bingham, Superintendent

post_text: Middle School students are all set to go to the Woodland Park Zoo on Monday. We will be leaving at 8:05 AM, and returning by 6:00 PM. Tomorrow is the last day students are able to turn in their permission slips to attend the field trip, they can't be accepted Monday morning because I turn in my final head count at 10 AM on Friday. I will send a separate email to those of you who have been approved to Chaperone our trip with some additional information. It should be a fun day!

I am excited to announce that the School Board and our local Teachers’ Association (CEA) have ratified a three year contract that provides for competitive wages and other provisions that will allow the district to recruit and keep top level staff. We know that the most important factor in student achievement is good instruction.

I want to thank the CEA representative officers that bargained in good faith and the interests of students as their primary focus.

David Bingham, Superintendent

Back to school event and All school BBQ will be Tuesday, August 27th.

Beginning at 4 PM. Students entering grades 6 -12 can report to the library by entering through the west door from the lower parking lot. Students and parents can update registration information, get their schedules, pay fees and much more.

Students and parents of students entering 1st -5th grade can visit their classroom.

Students entering kindergarten are welcome to visit school and attend the BBQ, but classroom visits will not be available.

We will serve hamburgers and hot dogs in the play shed area at 5 PM.

Call the school office if you have questions and we hope to see you there.

post_text:
Do you remember playing in your school band? Have you ever wanted to pick up that old trumpet, flute, or any other instrument that is collecting dust in the attic and start playing again? Well, here’s your chance!
We have put together a little pep band to play at school football games and basketball games during the school year. We would love to have any community member of any age to join us for these fun evenings! If you can only make one game, great! If you want to play during all the games, great!
Please email Evve Higgins at mhiggins@csd313.org for more information on dates, times, and copies of music. The selections are simple, but fun to play!

post_text: Tonight is our Volunteer appreciation reception in the Cafeteria. It is scheduled for 6:30. The majority of our middle and high school students will be joining students from several other schools on the Peninsula to watch the Tethered High Altitude Balloon Launch at Port Angeles High School. It is a great follow-up to the lab they participated in last semester on our Campus with representatives from NASA's NESSP (Northwest Earth and Space Science Pipeline. It should be an exciting event!

Students will be given additional information about how they can track the balloon itself from their phones tomorrow. We will be outside, so send your students dressed for the weather!

post_text:
Read Across America/Dr. Suess birthday activities. Our staff has been working on a couple activities beginning on Friday, March 1st. All of our students will participate in a buddy reading activity on Friday. Older students will visit elementary classes to read to or with our younger students at 9:00 AM.

As part of our staff professional development work on Wednesday's when students are released early our staff participate in Professional Learning Communities (PLC's) one Wednesday per month. One of the PLC groups is reading three different books this year and discussing how to support literacy in the classroom. There are elementary, middle and high school teachers in this group. To support literacy in the whole school they have organized DEAR (Drop Everything and Read). Next week as part of the Read Across America/Dr. Suess events everybody on campus, students, teachers and classified staff will DEAR for 20 minutes during the school day Monday through Friday.

post_text: Our 8th grade class had the opportunity to go to iFLY in Seattle yesterday, and they had an amazing time! They got to cement their knowledge about gravitational pull, drag force and terminal velocity. They were able to apply their engineering knowledge to build an apparatus that would reach it's terminal velocity in a miniature wind tunnel, and maintain its position for a full 10 seconds. And, best of all, they got to FLY too!

post_text:
A picture is worth a thousand words, but does not always tell the whole story. We began our 0 hour band class on Monday and the attendance has been as high as 10, but no less than 8 each morning with mostly middle school students currently participating. Students are still investigating instruments as most of them are true beginners. The district does own some instruments, but they have not been out of the cases for many years. We do have a friend of the music program lined up to come in and help us figure out what it will take to make them useful to a beginning band student. My goals is that all students who want to participate will have the opportunity without cost being a barrier. If you happen to have an instrument in working order, might be interested in sponsoring an instrument rental or some ability to evaluate instruments to get our students started please give me a call.

I was in the band class this morning and there is a buzz of excitement and we want to keep them interested and engaged.

David L. Bingham, Superintendent

post_text:
2nd SEMESTER BEGINNING BAND CLASS OFFERED

The district is currently involved in a strategic planning process and the planning team has identified music as an area where there is a need for increased opportunities for our students. We are excited to announce that we are going to begin offering a beginning band class for students in grades 6 -12 beginning second semester - January 28. Because of the challenges of developing a master schedule, this class will be offered from 7:00 a.m. to 7:50 a.m.. Music teacher Ms. Higgins is gathering information about instruments and developing the curriculum for the class. If you are a family that is homeschooling your children but would like your child to participate in a band program, they would also be welcome to enroll in the class. If you would like more information about the class or want to enroll your child in this class please contact Ms. Higgins or Mr. Bingham.

post_text:
Friday night in the Crescent School Library at 5:30 PM
Friday night there will be a presentation for parents of students in grades 4 - 12 on Circles 4 Hope a suicide prevention program that we are going to start under the leadership of Sherri Jones. Dr. Hudnall's presentation educates the community on the "Circles4Hope" model where everyone is taught that suicide prevention involves everyone. Suicide prevention, intervention and post intervention is discussed along with the current research on suicide and how families and communities can work together to prevent suicide. During the day Friday a core group of students and staff will attend some training. I hope that parents are able to attend.

post_text:
Mark your calendars for November 29, 2018 at 6PM. Daryl Trowbridge from Healthy Families of Clallam County will be in the library to talk about "bystander intervention" as it relates to Bullying. Daryl will provide strategies and tools to help parents to better interact with and support their children when the issues of bullying and relationships come up. Daryl presented at a recent staff meeting and will be presenting some mini lessons to our elementary and middle school class thorough out the school year. Daryl incorporates puppetry in his lessons that are designed for all age groups.

Sherri Jones will provide some information about the activities of our newly formed "suicide prevention" program and the Hope Squad Curriculum. Our Student Assistant Professional, Melissa Thetford will also attend this presentation. We hope you will take the time to attend this event.

post_text:
It's Red Ribbon Week® (October 23-31)!

The Red Ribbon Campaign® is the oldest and largest drug prevention program in the Nation and a way for people and communities to take a visible stand for healthy lifestyles. The campaign was created after DEA Agent Kiki Camarena was kidnapped and killed in Mexico in 1985. People began wearing red ribbons as a symbol of Kiki's sacrifice and to show their support for drug-free living. With approximately 74,000 American lives lost last year to drug overdose, your participation in Red Ribbon Week is more important than ever.

Our Crescent Coalition Leader, Tuesday Mattix and Student Assistance Professional, Melissa Thetford have been busy putting up displays in our display case and placing Red Ribbons around campus.
